Third-party components used at runtime (not redistributed in this source repo):
- Demucs (MIT) - drum source separation
- PyTorch (BSD-3) - Demucs backend
- yt-dlp (Unlicense) - audio download
- FFmpeg (LGPL/GPL, via imageio-ffmpeg) - audio decode/encode
- Deno (MIT) - JavaScript runtime for YouTube challenge solving
- PyGuitarPro (LGPL-3) - Guitar Pro parsing
- FastAPI, Uvicorn, pywebview, mido, numpy - see requirements.txt

Optional audio-only "full kit" drum-detection engines (models downloaded at
runtime to %LOCALAPPDATA%/DTXForge, NOT bundled or redistributed here):

- inagoy DrumSep ("Full kit" engine) - a Demucs (HDemucs) checkpoint that
  separates a drum stem into kick/snare/toms/cymbals.
  Source: https://github.com/inagoy/drumsep (checkpoint redistributed via
  https://github.com/ZFTurbo/Music-Source-Separation-Training). The upstream
  project states no explicit license; DTX Forge fetches it at runtime for the
  user's own use and does not redistribute the weights.

- LarsNet ("Full kit+" engine) - Mezza, Giampiccolo, Bernardini, Sarti,
  "Toward deep drum source separation," Pattern Recognition Letters 183 (2024).
  Source: https://github.com/polimi-ispl/larsnet. The UNet architecture file is
  vendored at dtxforge/vendor/larsnet_unet.py. The pretrained MODEL WEIGHTS are
  licensed CC BY-NC 4.0 (NON-COMMERCIAL) and are downloaded at runtime, never
  bundled. Charts you generate with this engine inherit that non-commercial
  restriction on the model's contribution; use the "Fast" or "Full kit" engine,
  or supply your own notation, if you need a commercial-safe pipeline.

DTX Forge's own source code remains MIT-licensed. The MIT license covers the
code only, not the third-party model weights fetched at runtime.

DTXMania is a separate project by its respective authors; this tool produces
files compatible with it but is not affiliated with or endorsed by it.
